 western Catholic Church (the Latin Church) it is called the Commemoration of All the Faithful Departed (), and is celebrated annually on 2 November. In the ordinary form of the Roman Rite, as well as in the Personal Ordinariates established by Benedict XVI for former Anglicans, it remains on 2 November if this date falls on a Sunday; in the 1962\u22121969 form of the Roman Rite, use of which is still authorized, it is transferred to Monday, 3 November. On this day in particular, Catholics pray for the dead. In the Church of England it is called The Commemoration of the Faithful Departed (All Souls' Day) and is an optional celebration; Anglicans view All Souls' Day as an extension of the observance of All Saints' Day and it serves to \"remember those who have died\", in connection with the theological doctrines of the resurrection of the body and the Communion of Saints. In the Eastern Orthodox Church and the associated Eastern Catholic Churches, it is celebrated several times during the year and is not associated with the month of November.", "qas": [{"question": "what day do the saints of all christians die ?", "answers": [], "id": "(23, 0, 0)"}]}, {"context": "Beliefs and practices associated with All Souls' Day vary widely among Christian churches and denominations.", "qas": [{"question": "what type of churches are in the christian church ?", "answers": [], "id": "(23, 1, 0)"}]}, {"context": "Among Eastern Orthodox and Byzantine (Greek) Catholics, there are several All Souls' Days during the year. Most of these fall on Saturday, since Jesus lay in the Tomb on Holy Saturday. They occur on the following occasions:", "qas": [{"question": "who are two eastern orthodox and byzantine greek christians ?", "answers": [], "id": "(23, 2, 0)"}]}, {"context": "In all of the Orthodox Church there is a commemoration of the dead on the Saturday before the feast of Saint Michael the Archangel\u20148 November, instead of the Demetrius Soul Saturday.", "qas": []}, {"context": "In