y the Jehovah's Witnesses, have been subjected to harassment, sometimes violently. All churches apart from the Armenian Apostolic Church must register with the government, and proselytizing was forbidden by law, though since 1997 the government has pursued more moderate policies. The government's policy toward conscientious objection is in transition, as part of Armenia's accession to the Council of Europe. Most of Armenia's ethnic Azeri population was deported in 1988\u20131989 and remain refugees, largely in Azerbaijan. Armenia's record on discrimination toward the few remaining national minorities is generally good. The government does not restrict internal or international travel. Although freedom of the press and speech are guaranteed, the government maintains its monopoly over television and radio broadcasting.", "qas": [{"question": "what is armenia ?", "answers": [], "id": "(37, 6, 0)"}]}, {"context": "In December 2015, the country held a referendum which approved transformation of Armenia from a semi-presidential to a parliamentary republic.", "qas": []}, {"context": "As a result, the president is stripped of his veto faculty and the presidency is downgraded to a figurehead position elected by parliament every seven years. The president is not allowed to be a member of any political party and re-election is forbidden. Having more immediate effects, the amendments reduced the number of parliamentary seats from 131 to 101.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Sceptics saw the constitutional reform as an attempt of third president Serzh Sargsyan to remain in control by becoming prime minister after fulfilling his second presidential term in 2018.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Until the ratification of the 2015 constitutional reform, the President was directly elected for a five-year term in a two-round system.", "qas": []}, {"context": "The unicameral National Assembly of Armenia (\"Azgayin Zhoghov\") is the legislative branch of the government of Armenia.", "qas": [{"ques